\begin_layout Definition
A 
\emph on
path
\emph default
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a parametric model 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in(0,\epsilon)$
\end_inset

 that is differentiable in quadratic mean with score function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The maximal tangent set is the the set of all such pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(p_{t},g)\}$
\end_inset

 projected onto the second coordinate.
 Any subset of the maximal tangent set is also a tanget set.
 We denote tangent sets by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
For each 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in T_{p}$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t}[g]$
\end_inset

 be the set of paths realizing 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The maximal tangent set is a cone,
 i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $aT\subset T$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

.
 This follows from the fact hat 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ta}$
\end_inset

 is a path whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t}$
\end_inset

 is,
 and the resulting score function is 
\begin_inset Formula $ag$
\end_inset

.
 Most tangent sets are also cones.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It suffices to work with tangent sets that are dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\text{span}T_{p}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}$
\end_inset

 is the maximal tangent set.
 A tangent set satisfying this condition is called 
\emph on
complete
\emph default
.
\end_layout

